  "texts": [
    "Based on the assumption that past events influence current events, the Hawkes process simulates a point process with an underlying self-exciting pattern.",
    "It is appropriate for modeling the evolution of discrete sequences.",
    "Given all historical events up to time, the probability of an event occurring in a short time interval at time can be defined by the conditional intensity function of the Hawkes process, denoted asλ * (t)= lim ∆t→0 E[H(t + ∆t) -H(t) | H(t)] ∆t = µ + t 0 g(t -s)dN(s),(1)H(t) t H(t) t ∆t H(t) t + ∆t t µ g(•) g(•) e -βt (β > 0) λ * (•) {t 1, t 2, t 3,...}where represents historical events prior to time, denotes the number of historical events that occurred before time, and indicates the window size.",
    "The first equation describes the probability that an event will occur in the region beyond the observed data.",
    "Specifically, it represents the probability that an event will occur at time based on prior observations up to time."
